[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]BCS, The Chartered Institute for IT[bold] (WSC084)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]There is 
[normal]a wealth of research demonstrating the value of diversity to 
[normal]UK
[normal] businesses, especially increasing the number of women operating on boards.  However, progress increasing the participation of women (particularly in IT) is slow.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our recommendations cover:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]W
[normal]e
[normal] know
[normal] that women choose IT as a profession less often than men
[normal], and that women 
[normal]leave the profession for other careers
[normal]. We would like to see this change, as there are 
[normal]exceptionally
[normal] good opportunities 
[normal]for
[normal] women
[normal] to
[normal] flourish in IT environments
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]BCS
[normal] 
[normal]believe
[normal]s
[normal] that the UK IT 
[normal]s
[normal]ector would be strengthened by innovation and pr
[normal]ofit benefits which diversity in the workplace brings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Today’s job market is very competitive
[normal];
[normal] IT is both the enabler of savings and the engine of growth, and people with skills and experience in IT are likely to be more in demand than people with other s
[normal]kill sets
[normal].
[normal] IT is integral to every business process, and IT teams interact with business teams, working together in exciting and dynamic environments to transform companies. Careers in IT can be varied, stimulating
[normal] and
[normal] flexible
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]However, it seems that fo
[normal]r many women IT isn’t regarded as a great place to 
[normal]work
[normal].
[normal]  WISE, formerly the UKRC
[normal] for Women in SET
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]has published the following
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The IT industry directly contributes 8% (£75 billion) to the U
[normal]K’s total GVA
[normal].
[normal]The scope of the value of IT to the UK economy transcends the IT sector alone, with around 40% of the IT workforce employed in other industries
[normal], 
[normal]benefiting business through increased efficiency provided by new technology. 
[normal]T
[normal]he McKinsey 
[normal]Reports; Women Matter
[normal] (2007)
[normal], and Women Matter 2
[normal] 
[normal](2010)
[normal], outline the benefits in 
[normal]RO
[normal]I
[normal], 
[normal]profit
[normal] and share-price
[normal] when boards and senior management teams include diverse members.
[normal]  W
[normal]ork by 
[normal]Cedric Herring, University of Illinois, in a paper
[normal] 
[normal]titled
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]Does Diversit
[normal]y Pay? Race, Gender, and
[normal] 
[normal]the Business Case for Diversity
[normal]’
[normal], 
[normal]examines the impact of racial and
[normal] 
[normal]gender diversity on business performance
[normal]. He makes a business case for diversity
[normal],
[normal] arguing that a diverse workforce produce
[normal]s
[normal] better results and offers a direct ROI.  His research, as with that of McKinsey
[normal],
[normal] promises larger profit and greater earnings.
[normal] 
[normal]Additionally
[normal], 
[normal]the law firm Reed Smith launched a report in partnership with Winmark showing how global companies could get the be
[normal]st ROI from gender diversity. The "
[normal]Gender Balancing: It's Good Business
[normal]" report
[normal] 
[normal]surveyed a range of FTSE100, FTSE250 and leading firms to determine UK businesses’ level of commitment to gender diversity and practical initiatives.
[normal]  
[normal]The report
[normal] found
[normal], as with the others cited here, 
[normal]that
[normal] overall business effectiveness and profit 
[normal]was
[normal] enhanced when women 
[normal]were
[normal] included in every level of enterprise
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]We have consulted with a number of industry stakeholders who all testify to the value of diversity in the i
[normal]ndustry:
[normal]Creating a diverse workforce at Thomson Reuters is a critical component of our vision and advances the focus on collaboration and innovation by bringing more women onto our technology teams. We are currently working on a program that we are callin
[normal]g, “from college to career”, which will build bridges from colleges to active careers at Thomson Reuters. Part of this initiative is the commitment to recruit and develop future female technology leaders. By creating more diverse teams we add another innov
[normal]ation dimension advancing future solutions and adding new perspectives and ideas.
[normal]Jane Moran, CIO, Thomson Reuters[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The leak of women into STEM starts in school and we see girls are not encouraged or properly advised of the richness of a career in IT, and 
[normal]the industry needs a style makeover to move on from the “geeky” back office image it still has. We tend to describe our roles in a very technical way expecting use of “cyber security” will be a major draw – and it is a turn off instead. The use of gaming, 
[normal]fun technology and more retail linked brands is much more 
[normal]helpful. Google, Amazon and e-bay don’t have the same problems the more traditional B to B service companies experience in attracting girls.
[normal]Ann Brown, Senior Vice President HR, Capgemini UK[bold]&#xa0;[bold]There 
[normal]aren’t any simple problems or challenges left.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Almost everything we do is beyond the capacity and capabilities of the individual.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] We depend entirely on the expanse of talent we can muster by bringing teams together, and like it or not, there are some thi
[normal]ngs that men and women do equally well, and there are a set of things that one does better than the other.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] If you don’t build teams with a balance of men and women, you’re building teams with unnecessary limitations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In Visa Europe we try and create these
[normal] balanced teams.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Starting in our Visa Apprentice programme and lasting as long as necessary, we provide accelerated development and support programmes and specifically for or female members of staff, to try and accelerate the slow but inevitable rebalanci
[normal]ng of men and women in all roles in business and technology. 
[normal]Steve Chambers, CIO, VISA[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Women are an integral and important part of our Global IT team at BG Group. BG Group believes that we will deliver better and more sustainable results if we have a cul
[normal]ture where different perspectives are encouraged and considered. To achieve this, we aim to build a workforce that is diverse – in ethnicity, gender, background and approach.
[normal]Angus McCallum, CIO, BG Group[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Women are leading key areas of our business from 
[normal]central technology services to strategy to content and are instrumental in our progress as an organisation. We believe that businesses which better reflect society, in all its diversity, will
[normal] 
[normal]be more successful in the long-term.
[normal]Selwyn Castleden, IS Direct[bold]or Sky[bold] [bold]Network Services, BskyB[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Creating an inclusive workplace is something that IBM has always set out to achieve. Diverse teams energise and challenge each other to deliver strong business results and innovative ideas which is why IBM in the UK and Irel
[normal]and continues to employee people from all lifestyles and backgrounds. It makes perfect business sense and is essential to the way we work and the way we operate our business.
[normal]David Stokes, IBM UK and Ireland General Manager[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]At Deloitte our business thrive
[normal]s on the many and varied talents of our people. The ability to attract, retain and advance talented women is an important part of this. We have set objectives to improve the representation of women in senior roles to ensure women have every opportunity to 
[normal]develop and progress. We recognise and highly value the qualities female leaders can bring to the business and are working within firm and the wider market to foster these strengths.
[normal]Rebecca George OBE, Partner Public Sector Health, Deloitte LLP[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4[bold]              [bold]C[bold]auses[bold] for the [bold]A[bold]bsence of [bold]W[bold]omen in IT[bold] and Best Practice [bold]Research
