[normal]4.1[bold] [bold]Cultures in[bold] the[bold] [bold]IT [bold]S[bold]ector [bold]W[bold]orkforce[bold]4.1.1 
[normal]              
[normal]A 
[normal]2005 
[normal]study conducted for Intellect and the DTI concluded that women were leaving the industry because they felt undervalued, found their management unsupportive, did not feel included in the male dominated industry, and felt the long hours culture
[normal] was 
[normal]un
[normal]comfortable for them
[normal];
[normal]4.1.2 
[normal]              
[normal]Women act differently from men in the workplace. 
[normal]Women sell themselves differently in interviews and performance appraisals.  In predominantly male environments, if men are not aware of these differences, women miss out 
[normal]on networking, mentoring and promotion opportunities
[normal]. Everywoman (
[normal]www.everywoman.com
[normal]) is an excellent example of an organisation providing advice, networking resources and connections to help women address the 
[normal]issues often faced by women in traditionally male dominated environments
[normal];
[normal]  
[normal]4.1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]M
[normal]any women report that the
[normal]re is an
[normal] 'old boys
[normal]’
[normal] network' 
[normal]culture 
[normal]creat
[normal]ing
[normal] a
[normal]n 
[normal]impenetrable
[normal] glass ceiling
[normal].
[normal] One recent statistic states that 58% of 
[normal]US 
[normal]male CEOs 
[normal]in the 500 largest compa
[normal]nies 
[normal]are over 
[normal]6f
[normal]t tall, whilst only 14% of the population are over that height
[normal], 
[normal]suggest
[normal]ing
[normal] deep rooted 
[normal]bias in the 
[normal]selection
[normal] of top executives
[normal];
[normal]4.1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Many 
[normal]words and phrases
[normal] 
[normal]crop up in research and interviews, including 
[normal]glass ceiling, glass cliff, 
[normal]macho/aggressive and bullying culture, lack of recognition, having to work extra hard to prove themselves, long hours culture, old-boys club.  If these
[normal] reflect
[normal] 
[normal]industry 
[normal]norms 
[normal]which 
[normal]impact the retention of women, they need to be addressed in order 
[normal]to 
[normal]stem t
[normal]he decline in women in the industry
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]4.1.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women
[normal] will be discriminated against even when the employer has policies which aim to do the right thing
[normal].  Gender Schemas
[normal], also known as 
[normal]u
[normal]nconscious 
[normal]b
[normal]ias
[normal], 
[normal]are 
[normal]socialised into the
[normal] 
[normal]populace from birth, 
[normal]and 
[normal]define the 
[normal]assumptions
[normal] by which individuals are judged.  This is particularly important when recruitment, promotion and 
[normal]performance 
[normal]assessment
[normal] 
[normal]decisions are made
[normal].  
[normal]4.[bold]2[bold] [bold]Image of Women in IT in the Media [bold]4.2.1
[normal]              
[normal]The UK
[normal] Government has invested in research into the roles that TV and the media play 
[normal]in gender stereotyping
[normal] and the
[normal]ir
[normal] effect on STEM career decisions
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]4.2.2
[normal]              
[normal]‘Media coverage of science, particularly television programmes, is a key 
[normal]place
[normal] 
[normal]where young peoples’ perc
[normal]eptions of STEM and its relationship with society are formed…the images young people see presented on television are generally thought to have some influence on the choices some students 
[normal]make about their future careers;
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]‘
[normal]4.2.3
[normal]              
[normal]In the UK
[normal] the numbers of women opting 
[normal]for
[normal] IT studies at university continues to fall
[normal].  W
[normal]e believe that without adequate positive representation in the 
[normal]m
[normal]edia young women will not choose careers in our industry
[normal],
[normal] despite the good work done by earlier programmes such 
[normal]as Computer Clubs for Girls
[normal] (CC4G)
[normal];
[normal]4.2.4
[normal]              
[normal]A relatively recent example of the power of media representations is the upswing in the take-up of Forensic Science courses by young women (women now represent two thirds
[normal] of
[normal] UK students on Forensic Science courses)
[normal].  This has been largely attributed to the portrayal of a female forensic pathologist in the BBC TV production 
[normal]Silent Witness
[normal].
[normal]4.[bold]3[bold] [bold]Lack of Role Models [bold]4.3.1
[normal]              
[normal]The lack of visible role models allow
[normal]s
[normal] gender and industry stereotypes to persist, to reinforce the ‘nerdy’ image of the IT or technical professional
[normal]s
[normal]. That these perceptions persist sustains the lack of attraction of the IT sector for young 
[normal]females
[normal]. It is simply not a career default choice. S
[normal]chools and HEIs find it difficult to challenge the stereotypes and offer girls an image of an exciting career in IT and technology.  Equally, 
[normal]if 
[normal]women already embarked on IT careers cannot see equality of opportunity and subsequent equality of reward in fe
[normal]male role models, they will opt for other industries where opportunities for advancement 
[normal]are visible.
[normal]4.3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Many organisations have built education outreach programmes, selecting and training women to go into schools to present on the benefits of women in IT. BC
[normal]S has been involved with a programme started by Deloitte and Atos and we are aware of other industry based schemes w
[normal]ith
[normal] the same motivations.  However, these schemes are voluntary, not 
[normal]incentivised
[normal] or rewarded, and funding is usually time bounded
[normal];
[normal]4.3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Other 
[normal]Ambassador s
[normal]chemes have had some success.  
[normal]Research cites prominent scientists, media personalities and teachers among the people who influence career choice, beyond members of the immediate family. The government funded scheme, science and engineering amb
[normal]assadors (SEAs) was established in 2000.  It increases the number of individuals in early 
[normal]career 
[normal]stages coming into contact with young
[normal]sters
[normal] 
[normal]through
[normal] schools science clubs, to talk about their work.  SEAs were established in recognition of the fact that few 
[normal]teachers have experience of working in industry, research or higher education.  Of those that do have relevant experience, by definition it will be limited and will date quickly, especially in fast moving areas such as IT
[normal];
[normal]4.3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Everywoman organisation is he
[normal]lping to address this through Leadership Academies; one day seminars for women in disciplines such as Technology, Engineering, Manufacturing, or Transport to boost their knowledge and be inspired by leading female figures as role models.
[normal]4.[bold]4[bold] [bold]Recruitment Po[bold]licies [bold] [bold]4.4.1
[normal]              
[normal]Where gendered names are removed from CVs in repeated trials and research, employers select males and females equally, based on the merits of skills
[normal];
[normal]4.4.2
[normal]              
[normal]Research suggests that 
[normal]using
[normal] female appropriate
[normal] recruitment
[normal] advertising will benefit targets for employing women and conversely that where advertising is not positively constructed to be attractive to women, 
[normal]fewer women apply
