[normal]5.1 [bold]Quotas[bold]The argument against 
[normal]q
[normal]uotas has been fierce, 
[normal]and resides around the desire for a meritocracy, and a desire that women succeed by right of their ability.  However, this pre-supposes that the current state of affairs represents a meritocracy
[normal], and that the industry will make progress through voluntary a
[normal]ctions.  Progress, however, continues to be slow and we therefore recommend that:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The debate should be reopened on setting q
[normal]uota
[normal]s for women in STEM in academia and industry sectors.  
[normal]This would include i
[normal]mplementation of monitoring and targets in all organi
[normal]sations on the uptake of women into senior management and executive 
[normal]and non-executive 
[normal]positions
[normal];
[normal]5.1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This debate should includ
[normal]e
[normal] consultation on legislation regarding t
[normal]he percentage of women on company boards
[normal], like 
[normal]countries, compelling state owned and listed 
[normal]private companies to appoint women to at least 30% of boardroom positions with severe penalties for those who do
[normal] not
[normal] conform;
